1
00:00:00,473 --> 00:00:01,894
[SPEAKER_04]: All right, welcome, everyone.

2
00:00:02,234 --> 00:00:09,300
[SPEAKER_04]: So first thing I want to do is some business, the minutes.

3
00:00:11,822 --> 00:00:13,324
[SPEAKER_04]: Did anyone have a chance to look at the minutes?

4
00:00:15,706 --> 00:00:16,206
[SPEAKER_03]: I did.

5
00:00:16,586 --> 00:00:18,648
[SPEAKER_03]: They seemed reasonable to me.

6
00:00:19,529 --> 00:00:21,290
[SPEAKER_03]: I move that we accept the minutes.

7
00:00:25,914 --> 00:00:27,095
[SPEAKER_04]: OK, all in favor?

8
00:00:27,896 --> 00:00:28,156
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

9
00:00:28,456 --> 00:00:29,157
[SPEAKER_04]: OK, great.

10
00:00:31,158 --> 00:00:38,403
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, so do we want to review what we talked about last time?

11
00:00:38,423 --> 00:00:44,747
[SPEAKER_03]: That sounds super reasonable to me.

12
00:00:45,248 --> 00:00:46,529
[SPEAKER_03]: Do you want me to share my screen?

13
00:00:46,569 --> 00:00:50,952
[SPEAKER_03]: I can show what it is that we started writing particularly.

14
00:00:51,632 --> 00:00:54,334
[SPEAKER_04]: Sure, let me give you the ability to do that.

15
00:01:00,844 --> 00:01:01,344
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, okay.

16
00:01:01,364 --> 00:01:02,445
[SPEAKER_04]: You should be able to do it now.

17
00:01:03,385 --> 00:01:03,605
[SPEAKER_04]: Great.

18
00:01:05,826 --> 00:01:23,174
[SPEAKER_03]: So the long story short is that we, um, created a folder for all of the documents that we're going to be working on here in Google docs and started just kind of taking notes first on the list of groups that we might empower generally.

19
00:01:23,194 --> 00:01:24,034
[SPEAKER_03]: Right.

20
00:01:24,154 --> 00:01:25,775
[SPEAKER_03]: So somewhat exhaustive list.

21
00:01:26,542 --> 00:01:35,690
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't imagine that like school committee chair, school committee will be something we're working on because that's not part of articles two and three, but they are still, we want to think about them.

22
00:01:37,171 --> 00:01:41,955
[SPEAKER_03]: If there's any powers that we might want to leave to them, I guess, basically.

23
00:01:41,975 --> 00:01:48,240
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, definitely the whole committee will talk about that, but the school committee subcommittee will also have a lot to say too, I'm sure.

24
00:01:48,680 --> 00:01:49,201
[SPEAKER_03]: Absolutely.

25
00:01:50,507 --> 00:01:58,814
[SPEAKER_03]: So I figured we could just start by listing those, and then we started making a list of all of the powers we could kind of imagine giving to any of these groups.

26
00:01:59,995 --> 00:02:15,948
[SPEAKER_03]: Some of them you'll see are crossed out because they're things that either we've decided a different subcommittee is going to talk about, for example, the budget, or because we feel that they're not part of articles two or three, for example, the charter amendment process and ordinances, et cetera.

27
00:02:17,883 --> 00:02:23,327
[SPEAKER_03]: I'll go ahead and share the link to this document in the chat so that you can see it, John.

28
00:02:23,347 --> 00:02:28,572
[SPEAKER_03]: Although it's, you know, publicly available as well.

29
00:02:29,612 --> 00:02:31,294
[SPEAKER_04]: It's in our folder, right?

30
00:02:31,454 --> 00:02:32,255
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, exactly.

31
00:02:33,115 --> 00:02:34,697
[SPEAKER_03]: But a little easier to find with that link.

32
00:02:37,259 --> 00:02:42,543
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, so, and we, last week we had some ideas about the committee,

33
00:02:44,801 --> 00:02:47,784
[SPEAKER_04]: committee and multi member body appointments, right?

34
00:02:48,705 --> 00:02:48,885
Yep.

35
00:02:49,946 --> 00:02:55,472
[SPEAKER_03]: So one thing I sent an email afterwards with a thing I was hoping to add to that.

36
00:02:56,253 --> 00:02:58,315
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, can you can you refresh on that?

37
00:02:59,597 --> 00:03:00,297
[SPEAKER_03]: Absolutely.

38
00:03:00,658 --> 00:03:03,000
[SPEAKER_03]: Let me see what I wrote so I can refresh my own memory.

39
00:03:04,122 --> 00:03:04,262
[SPEAKER_03]: Um,

40
00:03:05,813 --> 00:03:19,158
[SPEAKER_03]: Right, so one of the things we got talking about within appointments, giving the mayor appointment power, having the appointments take effect after 21 days, unless the city council acts to veto the appointment of a person.

41
00:03:23,860 --> 00:03:33,063
[SPEAKER_03]: The mayor can also remove people as they want from multi-member boards and commissions, again, subject to a similar city council override.

42
00:03:34,096 --> 00:03:36,818
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, and the city council can remove people by unanimous vote.

43
00:03:38,139 --> 00:03:41,022
[SPEAKER_03]: The piece that I was thinking we might want to add is.

44
00:03:41,762 --> 00:03:45,085
[SPEAKER_03]: At the moment, with the process for these committees.

45
00:03:46,046 --> 00:03:49,328
[SPEAKER_03]: The mayor puts out a call saying, hey, we have these openings.

46
00:03:50,169 --> 00:03:55,473
[SPEAKER_03]: Please send me applications basically, but the mayor is not required to make public who applied.

47
00:03:55,813 --> 00:04:00,557
[SPEAKER_03]: The mayor is not required to, like, respond to applications and then the quarter time.

48
00:04:01,520 --> 00:04:07,422
[SPEAKER_03]: Or at all, um, and I feel like for transparency reasons, we probably want.

49
00:04:08,162 --> 00:04:11,923
[SPEAKER_03]: Both of those things to be requirements, so the specific thing that I emailed about.

50
00:04:11,943 --> 00:04:20,146
[SPEAKER_03]: I said, I felt that the, um, the mayor should be required to respond to applicants directly who applied.

51
00:04:21,666 --> 00:04:23,727
[SPEAKER_03]: Assuming that the subcommittees have an opening, right?

52
00:04:23,747 --> 00:04:24,827
[SPEAKER_03]: Like, I don't think we need to.

53
00:04:26,763 --> 00:04:34,188
[SPEAKER_03]: open up a way in which somebody can legally harass the mayor and just be like, I'm applying to this, I'm applying to this, and require responses all the time.

54
00:04:34,829 --> 00:04:38,311
[SPEAKER_03]: But assuming that there's an opening, the mayor should have to respond.

55
00:04:39,332 --> 00:04:46,938
[SPEAKER_03]: And then there should be some public record of everybody who applied and whether or not they were appointed to a committee.

56
00:04:46,958 --> 00:04:50,921
[SPEAKER_03]: Again, just for transparency reasons.

57
00:04:52,081 --> 00:04:55,524
[SPEAKER_04]: Do you have thoughts on that, John?

58
00:04:56,929 --> 00:05:01,711
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, candidly, I think those sound like polite, nice things to do.

59
00:05:01,951 --> 00:05:03,091
[SPEAKER_01]: So I think you should do them.

60
00:05:03,252 --> 00:05:11,255
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't, I don't think that strikes me as a small mechanical thing that wouldn't belong in a charter in my estimation.

61
00:05:13,255 --> 00:05:19,878
[SPEAKER_01]: Frankly, I mean, as someone who's had applications come to me in other contexts, you do your best to reply in a timely way and

62
00:05:22,046 --> 00:05:26,048
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, I don't think establishing that as a mandate in the charter is something I would go for.

63
00:05:26,429 --> 00:05:26,909
[SPEAKER_04]: I agree.

64
00:05:26,969 --> 00:05:29,511
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't I don't wouldn't want to put it in the charter either.

65
00:05:29,731 --> 00:05:42,258
[SPEAKER_04]: And as far as the public record, I mean, I don't know about like, I mean, so the requiring a response is one thing.

66
00:05:42,298 --> 00:05:43,079
[SPEAKER_04]: And then there's the,

67
00:05:44,158 --> 00:05:47,641
[SPEAKER_04]: requirement to make public the applicants.

68
00:05:48,202 --> 00:05:50,203
[SPEAKER_04]: They are available.

69
00:05:50,364 --> 00:05:54,527
[SPEAKER_04]: Anybody can make a public records request and see.

70
00:05:55,368 --> 00:05:58,090
