01:12:08,150 --> 01:12:09,230
[SPEAKER_03]: Uh, yeah.

972
01:12:09,250 --> 01:12:11,231
[SPEAKER_03]: You can see in the city.

973
01:12:11,831 --> 01:12:12,231
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

974
01:12:12,351 --> 01:12:12,571
[SPEAKER_03]: Right.

975
01:12:13,711 --> 01:12:17,092
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, but this only happens if they aren't having a special election.

976
01:12:17,943 --> 01:12:26,190
[SPEAKER_04]: Right, so we probably don't want to say that the president of the city council immediately becomes acting mayor because then we create a vacancy on the city council, right?

977
01:12:26,210 --> 01:12:26,810
[SPEAKER_07]: Right.

978
01:12:26,950 --> 01:12:33,675
[SPEAKER_04]: But it's unclear what happens between the time that there's a vacancy and the time of the special election.

979
01:12:35,217 --> 01:12:36,237
[SPEAKER_04]: Is there just no mayor?

980
01:12:36,257 --> 01:12:39,160
[SPEAKER_03]: For the Melrose one, yeah, it's not clear here.

981
01:12:48,050 --> 01:12:54,213
[SPEAKER_03]: So for Pittsfield, they have the city council shall serve as acting mayor until the vacancy is filled.

982
01:12:54,413 --> 01:12:54,693
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

983
01:12:54,993 --> 01:12:55,133
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

984
01:12:55,313 --> 01:12:58,275
[SPEAKER_03]: Which is what I wrote the first time through.

985
01:12:59,075 --> 01:13:01,636
[SPEAKER_03]: And it doesn't say that they lose their job as city council.

986
01:13:01,656 --> 01:13:01,776
[SPEAKER_03]: Right.

987
01:13:01,976 --> 01:13:03,157
[SPEAKER_03]: So they would do both?

988
01:13:03,557 --> 01:13:04,257
[SPEAKER_03]: They're doing both.

989
01:13:05,118 --> 01:13:05,538
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't know.

990
01:13:05,618 --> 01:13:06,858
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't like that.

991
01:13:10,360 --> 01:13:15,282
[SPEAKER_04]: Because they're supposed to be two different branches, right?

992
01:13:16,413 --> 01:13:22,574
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't know, but I think the idea is that as acting mayor, you have fewer powers, right?

993
01:13:23,695 --> 01:13:27,335
[SPEAKER_04]: We would have to delineate that, I guess.

994
01:13:28,015 --> 01:13:29,736
[SPEAKER_01]: That was the issue in Boston a couple of years ago.

995
01:13:31,156 --> 01:13:31,456
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

996
01:13:32,556 --> 01:13:34,977
[SPEAKER_04]: That the acting mayor didn't have the same powers.

997
01:13:35,537 --> 01:13:37,578
[SPEAKER_01]: It's like you could act in emergencies.

998
01:13:38,718 --> 01:13:44,399
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, the acting mayor will have only those powers of the mayor as are indefensible and essential to the conduct of the business.

999
01:13:45,195 --> 01:13:47,516
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

1000
01:13:47,776 --> 01:13:48,456
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

1001
01:13:51,117 --> 01:13:53,017
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

1002
01:13:53,037 --> 01:13:58,939
[SPEAKER_01]: So maybe, maybe we adapt this for that interim period between them.

1003
01:14:00,099 --> 01:14:06,120
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, I think the other approach we could take is just the, the president of the city council can appoint an acting mayor.

1004
01:14:07,401 --> 01:14:11,902
[SPEAKER_03]: Whoever they, you know, I think there could be either from among the city council.

1005
01:14:14,252 --> 01:14:23,539
[SPEAKER_03]: Or, uh, you know, I think it could also be a really reasonable to say, um, they can appoint themselves themselves or department head.

1006
01:14:23,559 --> 01:14:26,801
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

1007
01:14:26,841 --> 01:14:29,123
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm not seeing the department head idea, but I kind of like it.

1008
01:14:29,904 --> 01:14:42,313
[SPEAKER_03]: I have to say, um, I think it makes a lot of sense to be able to, or, you know, to explicitly be able to appoint a department head, somebody who's like already probably well aware of how the city is run.

1009
01:14:46,517 --> 01:14:46,917
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

1010
01:14:48,738 --> 01:14:49,878
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, I like this.

1011
01:14:53,960 --> 01:14:54,961
[SPEAKER_04]: All right, good.

1012
01:14:57,001 --> 01:15:01,563
[SPEAKER_03]: Should we say, yeah, acting mayor.

1013
01:15:03,864 --> 01:15:04,365
[SPEAKER_03]: Acting mayor.

1014
01:15:04,425 --> 01:15:07,246
[SPEAKER_04]: I just wrote down delineate powers of acting mayor.

1015
01:15:08,066 --> 01:15:08,606
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

1016
01:15:08,666 --> 01:15:12,348
[SPEAKER_04]: So that we can just know that that has to be looked at.

1017
01:15:14,268 --> 01:15:15,569
[SPEAKER_01]: just act when necessary.

1018
01:15:21,253 --> 01:15:26,437
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, we're getting close to the end of article two, right?

1019
01:15:26,997 --> 01:15:28,999
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, I didn't actually order these.

1020
01:15:29,119 --> 01:15:30,480
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, you didn't organize it that way.

1021
01:15:30,520 --> 01:15:31,580
[SPEAKER_04]: This is just a list.

1022
01:15:31,600 --> 01:15:33,842
[SPEAKER_01]: Just a list, yeah.

1023
01:15:34,723 --> 01:15:36,044
[SPEAKER_01]: I think we'll end up hitting everything.

1024
01:15:36,144 --> 01:15:37,665
[SPEAKER_01]: Maybe actually, maybe after.

1025
01:15:37,685 --> 01:15:38,826
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't know, not tonight.

1026
01:15:38,866 --> 01:15:40,487
[SPEAKER_04]: We only have 10 minutes left.

1027
01:15:41,207 --> 01:15:43,349
[SPEAKER_01]: No, I didn't mean tonight.

1028
01:15:44,080 --> 01:15:44,600
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, okay.

1029
01:15:44,620 --> 01:15:45,721
[SPEAKER_04]: I thought you meant tonight.

1030
01:15:45,981 --> 01:15:46,461
[SPEAKER_01]: No, no.

1031
01:15:46,881 --> 01:15:48,462
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm going to bed as soon as this calls over.

1032
01:15:49,422 --> 01:15:49,823
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

1033
01:15:53,044 --> 01:15:56,105
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, so the next section is oversight.

1034
01:15:59,727 --> 01:16:00,247
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, yeah.

1035
01:16:02,928 --> 01:16:04,469
[SPEAKER_04]: So what have we seen?

1036
01:16:04,489 --> 01:16:07,110
[SPEAKER_04]: Is there an oversight section in the other charters?

1037
01:16:08,451 --> 01:16:10,232
[SPEAKER_01]: There's access to information in a few.

1038
01:16:12,653 --> 01:16:12,753
[SPEAKER_01]: Um,

1039
01:16:14,178 --> 01:16:34,510
[SPEAKER_03]: So specifically when I was thinking of oversight, I guess one thing is, uh, you know, coming back to the idea of the auditor, which I think we can table for now, but also just like, can the city council, should the city council have the explicit ability to compel information from basically any, uh, you know, city employee?

1040
01:16:35,851 --> 01:16:41,334
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, should the mayor be required to give a state of the city report?

1041
01:16:42,715 --> 01:16:42,835
[SPEAKER_03]: Um,

1042
01:16:43,658 --> 01:16:57,910
[SPEAKER_03]: What happens if a city counselor, or, you know, a can the city council force the mayor to attend meetings, and the city council force other counselors were, you know, absent to attend meetings, etc.

1043
01:17:01,289 --> 01:17:17,026
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't know if I would put it as the city council can force the mayor, but we have heard feedback from members of the public that the mayor should have to attend, well, some people think every city council meeting or periodic meetings.

1044
01:17:17,907 --> 01:17:18,487
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, go ahead.

1045
01:17:22,620 --> 01:17:25,582
[SPEAKER_01]: No, Framingham has a nice section that calls access to information.

1046
01:17:25,823 --> 01:17:34,650
[SPEAKER_01]: And it basically amounts to city officials and the mayor having to appear to speak to particular issues, provide certain information, that kind of thing.

1047
01:17:35,330 --> 01:17:36,171
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think that makes sense.

1048
01:17:38,813 --> 01:17:45,859
[SPEAKER_04]: So is, oh, here's the access to information section.

1049
01:17:49,258 --> 01:17:53,099
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, so in Melrose, any city officer?

1050
01:17:55,999 --> 01:17:57,980
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, so I mean, this usually happens.

1051
01:17:58,080 --> 01:18:13,443
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, you know, they usually ask, this just sort of says that the department head can't, I don't think they usually get turned down, but, or the, or the employee, but, but that's, that's reasonable.

1052
01:18:13,863 --> 01:18:14,623
[SPEAKER_04]: And the mayor,

1053
01:18:17,000 --> 01:18:20,781
[SPEAKER_04]: This does, yeah, this one does say may require the mayor to appear.

1054
01:18:27,162 --> 01:18:29,342
[SPEAKER_04]: So, okay.

1055
01:18:29,542 --> 01:18:39,884
[SPEAKER_04]: So this says the mayor can bring someone else, but like now I think sometimes the chief of staff will go to meetings, right?

1056
01:18:40,064 --> 01:18:40,844
[SPEAKER_04]: But not the mayor.

1057
01:18:42,404 --> 01:18:46,045
[SPEAKER_04]: And if this were in the charter, the mayor would have to go.

1058
01:18:47,366 --> 01:18:47,626
[SPEAKER_07]: Right.

1059
01:18:48,266 --> 01:18:48,787
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah.

1060
01:18:48,807 --> 01:18:50,967
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, and then the chief of staff.

1061
01:18:51,868 --> 01:18:52,048
[SPEAKER_07]: Right.

1062
01:18:52,788 --> 01:18:53,048
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

1063
01:18:53,308 --> 01:19:00,211
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, and, and even you can bring the chief of staff and the city council can't stop you from bringing people to help, which I think is also very reasonable.

1064
01:19:00,771 --> 01:19:01,231
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

1065
01:19:01,251 --> 01:19:11,155
[SPEAKER_01]: You have to give notice, which I think we should require because I think just having saying the mayor has to come tomorrow is, is unreasonable.

1066
01:19:11,935 --> 01:19:12,536
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

1067
01:19:12,636 --> 01:19:15,537
[SPEAKER_03]: I even think honestly, 48 hours is pretty unreasonable.

1068
01:19:15,897 --> 01:19:16,097
[SPEAKER_03]: Like.

1069
01:19:17,062 --> 01:19:22,223
[SPEAKER_03]: I think a week or two is much more reasonable.

1070
01:19:23,383 --> 01:19:41,228
[SPEAKER_04]: So this is different than what we were, you know, what has been proposed by some people saying that the mayor should be specifically required to go periodically, like once a month or, I mean, I feel like this makes more sense because.

1071
01:19:41,248 --> 01:19:42,888
[SPEAKER_01]: I do too.

1072
01:19:43,405 --> 01:19:50,329
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, the mayor just goes, if there's not really a reason to be there or, I mean, not that there isn't a reason.

1073
01:19:50,369 --> 01:19:55,112
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, being at the meetings, I guess is, um, its own reward.

1074
01:19:55,572 --> 01:19:56,453
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

1075
01:19:57,674 --> 01:20:02,657
[SPEAKER_04]: But, um, but I feel like this is, this is a better use of time.

1076
01:20:03,677 --> 01:20:04,018
[SPEAKER_01]: I agree.

1077
01:20:04,918 --> 01:20:06,559
[SPEAKER_01]: The meetings can go for hours.

1078
01:20:07,059 --> 01:20:08,560
[SPEAKER_01]: The mayor's not going to be called upon.

1079
01:20:08,580 --> 01:20:09,441
[SPEAKER_01]: She shouldn't have to be there.

1080
01:20:10,185 --> 01:20:13,949
[SPEAKER_01]: Harmon Zuckerman, PB – He, Him, His): But at the same time, maybe they want or three meetings in a row, something's going on.

1081
01:20:13,969 --> 01:20:14,969
[SPEAKER_01]: I think that's also valid.

1082
01:20:16,471 --> 01:20:16,631
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

1083
01:20:16,651 --> 01:20:16,831
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

1084
01:20:17,071 --> 01:20:28,302
[SPEAKER_04]: And the, I think the The impetus behind the comment that the mayor should be required to go to the meetings comes from

1085
01:20:29,260 --> 01:20:40,966
[SPEAKER_04]: this desire to have the mayor and the city council have a less contentious relationship and, you know, um, and, and sort of making them really work together kind of.

1086
01:20:40,986 --> 01:20:43,187
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, that's what we've heard from people.

1087
01:20:43,267 --> 01:20:50,831
[SPEAKER_04]: So, um, so that's kind of, that's the goal of, of that ask.

1088
01:20:52,812 --> 01:20:56,434
[SPEAKER_03]: So there are a couple of differences I'm seeing in reading through these really quick.

1089
01:20:57,295 --> 01:20:57,875
[SPEAKER_03]: One of them.

1090
01:20:59,328 --> 01:21:24,395
[SPEAKER_03]: is um so like way myth gives the uh ability to subpoena a witness and administer oaths um which is a little more intense than what the other groups get um that's something i'd want to know more about that's a significant power you know yeah um

1091
01:21:26,399 --> 01:21:28,661
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's to, you know, to town office.

1092
01:21:28,761 --> 01:21:32,005
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, and then the other one that was interesting is Pittsfield.

1093
01:21:32,065 --> 01:21:47,340
[SPEAKER_03]: They also can require a member of a multi-member body, um, which like, it doesn't feel entirely unreasonable, but on the other hand, like volunteers.

1094
01:21:47,360 --> 01:21:49,302
[SPEAKER_04]: I exactly.

1095
01:21:49,982 --> 01:21:50,062
[SPEAKER_03]: Um,

1096
01:21:51,843 --> 01:21:52,143
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

1097
01:21:52,583 --> 01:21:59,026
[SPEAKER_03]: And even this, like, I think this would be reasonable if it was like require the chair of a multi-member body maybe, right?

1098
01:21:59,066 --> 01:22:03,688
[SPEAKER_03]: Like if you're the person in charge of this thing, that's more reasonable.

1099
01:22:03,708 --> 01:22:06,950
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, it's still, yeah.

1100
01:22:09,891 --> 01:22:14,573
[SPEAKER_04]: Um, well, um, I don't know.

1101
01:22:14,653 --> 01:22:16,314
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, I like Melrose.

1102
01:22:18,287 --> 01:22:21,350
[SPEAKER_04]: I think the way Melrose's is written is pretty good.

1103
01:22:22,290 --> 01:22:25,873
[SPEAKER_04]: And the question is, do we want to add the multi-member bodies?

1104
01:22:28,415 --> 01:22:33,098
[SPEAKER_01]: I guess my, I kind of like it, you know, cause they do play important roles.

1105
01:22:34,620 --> 01:22:40,324
[SPEAKER_01]: Like that's the assessors, you know, they're doing important work.

1106
01:22:42,786 --> 01:22:45,768
[SPEAKER_01]: You just have to hope that the council doesn't use it as an excuse to berate.

1107
01:22:46,592 --> 01:22:51,133
[SPEAKER_01]: people or, you know, it's not bad.

1108
01:22:51,213 --> 01:22:54,594
[SPEAKER_01]: To a certain degree, we have to assume good behavior on everyone's part.

1109
01:22:55,274 --> 01:22:56,255
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm good with it.

1110
01:22:56,635 --> 01:23:00,076
[SPEAKER_01]: I understand the hesitancy.

1111
01:23:01,096 --> 01:23:04,857
[SPEAKER_03]: Would you all be comfortable with, Melrose has 48 hours notice.

1112
01:23:06,458 --> 01:23:07,958
[SPEAKER_03]: Pittsfield has a week notice.

1113
01:23:10,059 --> 01:23:14,180
[SPEAKER_03]: It looks like Duane has five days.

1114
01:23:16,039 --> 01:23:20,183
[SPEAKER_03]: I think like at least a week, if not two.

1115
01:23:20,883 --> 01:23:21,164
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

1116
01:23:21,404 --> 01:23:23,726
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, if it's substantive, you want people to prepare.

1117
01:23:24,927 --> 01:23:25,247
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

1118
01:23:26,048 --> 01:23:33,775
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, just like if you were planning your, you know, once in a lifetime trip to France or something.

1119
01:23:33,815 --> 01:23:35,656
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, exactly.

1120
01:23:35,676 --> 01:23:36,417
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean,

1121
01:23:39,738 --> 01:23:41,919
[SPEAKER_04]: So the city council meets every other week.

1122
01:23:42,059 --> 01:23:51,584
[SPEAKER_04]: So, you know, if there's that, it has to fit into one of those meetings, unless they can also compel people to come to subcommittee meetings.

1123
01:23:52,104 --> 01:23:54,365
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, I'm assuming they could, right.

1124
01:23:55,526 --> 01:23:56,206
[SPEAKER_04]: It's any meeting.

1125
01:23:56,947 --> 01:24:01,529
[SPEAKER_04]: So it could happen at any time because those meetings happen and committees as a whole.

1126
01:24:01,549 --> 01:24:04,931
[SPEAKER_03]: Let's start with 10 days notice.

1127
01:24:05,251 --> 01:24:06,992
[SPEAKER_03]: That feels like a reasonable amount.

1128
01:24:08,979 --> 01:24:14,402
[SPEAKER_03]: I realize it's longer than what anybody else put, but, um, yeah.

1129
01:24:14,762 --> 01:24:16,283
[SPEAKER_03]: Like, uh, yeah.

1130
01:24:16,844 --> 01:24:17,384
[SPEAKER_04]: But you're right.

1131
01:24:17,444 --> 01:24:25,048
[SPEAKER_04]: It could run into a situation where the person is, you know, like as a trip to France plan, but nobody's going to be unreasonable.

1132
01:24:25,068 --> 01:24:26,089
[SPEAKER_07]: Right.

1133
01:24:26,209 --> 01:24:29,251
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, it doesn't say what the consequences to the person are.

1134
01:24:29,271 --> 01:24:29,511
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

1135
01:24:29,571 --> 01:24:29,611
[SPEAKER_04]: Um,

1136
01:24:35,007 --> 01:24:40,372
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I mean if you can subpoena... But if the person doesn't come with a good reason, it's fine.

1137
01:24:40,853 --> 01:24:41,053
[SPEAKER_03]: Right.

1138
01:24:41,473 --> 01:24:42,234
[SPEAKER_04]: People are reasonable.

1139
01:24:42,294 --> 01:24:47,118
[SPEAKER_03]: Subpoena witnesses is certainly a bit more... It's really intense.

1140
01:24:47,759 --> 01:24:48,159
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

1141
01:24:52,003 --> 01:24:52,383
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

1142
01:24:53,504 --> 01:24:57,168
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not sure I would... It sounds to me like we're uncomfortable with the subpoena witnesses thing.

1143
01:24:57,408 --> 01:24:57,848
[SPEAKER_03]: I am.

1144
01:24:57,948 --> 01:24:58,669
[SPEAKER_03]: I think that's fine.

1145
01:25:03,927 --> 01:25:12,133
[SPEAKER_03]: So then, so that includes compelling mayoral attendance of meetings, which I think is good.

1146
01:25:12,153 --> 01:25:23,862
[SPEAKER_03]: It covers, we don't want city council to be able to call random citizens and force them to come, I assume.

1147
01:25:23,882 --> 01:25:25,243
[SPEAKER_05]: No.

1148
01:25:25,824 --> 01:25:26,124
[SPEAKER_03]: Right.

1149
01:25:33,644 --> 01:25:37,366
[SPEAKER_03]: So then what that leaves is, um, I guess for.

1150
01:25:38,126 --> 01:25:39,767
[SPEAKER_04]: It was more than mayoral attendance.

1151
01:25:39,867 --> 01:25:42,689
[SPEAKER_04]: It was city employees too, right?

1152
01:25:43,209 --> 01:25:43,429
[SPEAKER_03]: Right.

1153
01:25:43,509 --> 01:25:44,110
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

1154
01:25:46,351 --> 01:25:49,172
[SPEAKER_03]: Plus city employees and multi-member bodies.

1155
01:25:50,033 --> 01:26:00,298
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, I wrote Melrose's as good as kind of a, uh, mainly focusing on, we want to add multi-member bodies and 10 days notice.

1156
01:26:00,859 --> 01:26:02,980
[SPEAKER_04]: And not school committee, not putting that in there.

1157
01:26:05,581 --> 01:26:11,465
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, the other ones don't have school school committee is very regulated.

1158
01:26:11,485 --> 01:26:14,467
[SPEAKER_04]: It's more regulated by the state than other bodies.

1159
01:26:14,547 --> 01:26:18,110
[SPEAKER_04]: So, but I don't know why it wouldn't be okay.

1160
01:26:18,270 --> 01:26:18,650
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't know.

1161
01:26:20,491 --> 01:26:21,132
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't know.

1162
01:26:21,872 --> 01:26:27,916
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, the city council doesn't really have anything to do with the schools other than approving the budget.

1163
01:26:28,417 --> 01:26:30,038
[SPEAKER_04]: So maybe it's not appropriate.

1164
01:26:30,666 --> 01:26:32,387
